{{multiple issues|{{one source|date=December 2013}}{{primary sources|date=December 2013}}}} {{DISPLAYTITLE:''Billboard'' Year-End Hot 100 singles of 2011}} [[File:Adele - Seattle, WA - 8.12.2011.jpg|thumb|right|190px|[[Adele (singer)|Adele]]'s "[[Rolling in the Deep]]" was the number 1 song of the year, topping the [[Hot 100]] for 7 consecutive weeks.]] [[File:California Dreams Tour-Seattle.jpg|thumb|right|190px|Four of [[Katy Perry|Katy Perry's]] singles, "[[Firework (song)|Firework]]", "[[E.T. (song)|E.T.]]", "[[Last Friday Night (T.G.I.F.)]]" and "[[Teenage Dream (Katy Perry song)|Teenage Dream]]" managed to enter the list, with "Firework" and "E.T." being numbers 3 and 4 respectively.]] [[File:Rihanna, LOUD Tour, Belfast cropped 2.jpg|thumb|right|190px|[[Barbados|Barbadian]] singer [[Rihanna]] had six songs to be included on the list, four of which were from her fifth album, ''[[Loud (Rihanna album)|Loud]]'', one from her sixth album, ''[[Talk That Talk (Rihanna album)|Talk That Talk]]'', and one feature on a [[Kanye West]] single.]] [[File:Bruno Mars 2010.jpg|thumb|right|190px|[[Bruno Mars]]' single "[[Just the Way You Are (Bruno Mars song)|Just the Way You Are]]" jumped three spots from last year's list, from 18 to 15.]] [[File:Nicki Minaj - Live Femme Fatale 9.jpg|thumb|right|190px|[[Nicki Minaj]]'s single "[[Super Bass]]" was number 8 on the list, as it peaked at number 3 at the [[Hot 100]], which made her the first female rapper to hit top 5 since [[Missy Elliott|Missy Elliott's]] song "[[Lose Control (Missy Elliott song)|Lose Control]]".]] [[File:DEV at 2011 MMVA.jpg|thumb|right|190px|Singer [[Dev (singer)|Dev]] had three songs from three different albums on the list. "[[Like a G6]]" by [[Far East Movement]], a former number one on the [[Hot 100]] list from the album ''[[Free Wired]]'', her solo single "[[In the Dark (Dev song)|In the Dark]]" from her debut album ''[[The Night the Sun Came Up]]'' and another featured single "[[Backseat (song)|Backseat]]" by [[New Boyz]] from their album ''[[Too Cool to Care]]''.]] ''[[Billboard (magazine)|Billboard]]'' publishes annual lists of songs based on chart performance over the course of a year based on [[Nielsen Broadcast Data Systems]] and [[Nielsen SoundScan|SoundScan]] information. For 2011, the list of the top 100 [[Billboard Hot 100|''Billboard'' Hot 100]] [[Billboard Year-End|Year-End]] songs was published on December&nbsp;9, calculated with data from December&nbsp;4, 2010 to November&nbsp;26, 2011. At the number one position was [[Adele (singer)|Adele]]'s "[[Rolling in the Deep]]", which stayed atop the Hot 100 for seven consecutive weeks, and in the top thirty for most of the year.
