{{primary sources|date=December 2013}} {{DISPLAYTITLE:''Billboard'' Year-End Hot 100 singles of 2012}} [[File:Gotye, 2012.jpg|thumb|right|190px|[[Gotye]]'s single, "[[Somebody That I Used to Know]]", came in at number one, spending a total of 8 weeks at number one throughout the year.]] [[File:Rihanna 2012.jpg|thumb|right|190px|Barbadian singer [[Rihanna]]'s "[[We Found Love]]" came in at number 69 in 2011 and rose to position 8 this year. She had a total of six songs included on the list, with her as a lead artist on 5 songs. Four of which were from her sixth album ''[[Talk That Talk (Rihanna album)|Talk That Talk]]'', and one was from her seventh album ''[[Unapologetic (album)|Unapologetic]]''.]] [[File:Katy Perry UNICEF 2, 2012.jpg|thumb|right|190px|Three of [[Katy Perry]]'s singles from ''[[Teenage Dream (Katy Perry album)|Teenage Dream:The Complete Confection]]'' are in the top 50, with "[[Wide Awake (Katy Perry song)|Wide Awake]]" at 15, "[[Part of Me (Katy Perry song)|Part of Me]]" at 31, and "[[The One That Got Away (Katy Perry song)|The One That Got Away]]" at 41.]] [[File:David Guetta at 2011 MMVA.jpg|thumb|right|190px|Three of [[David Guetta]]'s singles charted in the top 50, including the hit single "[[Titanium (song)|Titanium]]" at 24.]] [[File:Flo Rida2012.jpg|thumb|right|190px|All of rapper [[Flo Rida]]'s singles off of ''[[Wild Ones (album)|Wild Ones]]'' are within the top 20.]] [[File:Sia Furler in concert.jpg|thumb|right|190px|Singer [[Sia Furler|Sia]] is featured in 4 songs on the chart, despite not being the lead singer of them. "[[Wild Ones (song)|Wild Ones]]" by [[Flo Rida]] and "[[Titanium (song)|Titanium]]" by [[David Guetta]] feature her vocals, while the other two were written by her, "[[Diamonds (Rihanna song)|Diamonds]]" by [[Rihanna]] and "[[Let Me Love You (Until You Learn to Love Yourself)]]" by [[Ne-Yo]], which charted at 94 and 74 respectively.]] [[File:Ellie Goulding at Manchester Academy 2012 - Portrait.jpg|thumb|right|190px|Singer [[Ellie Goulding]], whose single "[[Lights (Ellie Goulding song)|Lights]]" appeared at number 5, is the highest-ranking British artist on the list.]] ''[[Billboard (magazine)|Billboard]]'' publishes annual lists of songs based on chart performance over the course of a year based on [[Nielsen Broadcast Data Systems]] and [[Nielsen SoundScan|SoundScan]] information. For 2012, the list for the top 100 [[Billboard Hot 100|''Billboard'' Hot 100]] [[Billboard Year-End|Year-End]] songs was published on December&nbsp;14, calculated with data from December&nbsp;3, 2011 to November 24, 2012.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.billboard.com/articles/news/1481472/the-best-of-2012-the-year-in-music?page=0%2C1|title=The Best of 2012: The Year In Music|year=2012|work=[[Billboard (magazine)|Billboard]]|publisher=[[Prometheus Global Media]]|accessdate=December 8, 2012}}</ref> At the number-one position was [[Gotye]]'s "[[Somebody That I Used to Know]]" featuring [[Kimbra]], which stayed atop the Hot 100 for eight consecutive weeks. {| class="wikitable sortable" style="font-size:90%; text-align: center" |+ List of songs on ''[[Billboard (magazine)|Billboard]]''{{'s}} 2012 [[Billboard Year-End|Year-End]] [[Billboard Hot 100|Hot 100]] chart<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.billboard.com/charts/year-end/2012/hot-100-songs|title=Hot 100 Songs Music Chart|year=2012|work=[[Billboard (magazine)|Billboard]]|publisher=[[Prometheus Global Media]]|accessdate=December 8, 2012}}</ref> |- ! scope="col" style="background:#dde;"| № ! scope="col" style="background:#dde;"| Title ! scope="col" style="background:#dde;"| Artist(s) |- ! scope="row" | 1 | "[[Somebody That I Used to Know]]" || [[Gotye]] featuring [[Kimbra]] |- ! scope="row" | 2 | "[[Call Me Maybe]]" || [[Carly Rae Jepsen]] |- ! scope="row" | 3 | "[[We Are Young]]" || [[Fun (band)|fun.]] featuring [[Janelle Monáe]] |- ! scope="row" | 4 | "[[Payphone (song)|Payphone]]" || [[Maroon 5]] featuring [[Wiz Khalifa]] |- ! scope="row" | 5 | "[[Lights (Ellie